Data Loading¶

(!)As a future reference, all code has been commented on for further clarification. All markdown has been written only for a general overview of each section.(!)¶

With the dataset being too large, we find that simply opening the file is impossible. Thus we start streaming each line, reading all neccecary and writing it on a seperate file.

Filtered Businesses¶

The CSV of filtered businesses, contains all businesses from Philadelphia that contain no Null/None values. This seperation was done during the filtering instead of relying on Pandas. We translate each line into its JSON equivilant, and check if there is a None value. If there is, we throw it out. If there's not, we check if it's from Philadelphia, and if it is we add it to the CSV. Note, that we also store in our memory the Business ID for the reviews. If there were too many businesses to keep their IDs in memory, a similar Streaming tactic would have been needed.

Filtered Reviews¶

The CSV of filtered reviews, contains all reviews that belong to the businesses of Filtere Businesses CSV. The process is similar from the above, with the only difference being that we drop all reviews that don't have a business_id field that has a match in our businessIDs list from the previous step.

Note: All data filtering, especially for the reviews, takes a good while. Roughly 30 minutes is required for all the filtering, so be patient.

In [ ]:
#Step 1: Stream-Read Business Dataset, Filter the IDs from Philadelphia, Store them to fetch businesses.
outputFileBusiness = open("filtered_business.csv", 'w', newline='')
businessIDs = []

with open("yelp_academic_dataset_business.json", errors="ignore") as f:
    buffer = ["business_id","name","address","city","state","postal code", "latitude",
              "longitude", "stars", "review_count", "is_open", "attributes",
              "categories","hours"]
    writer = csv.writer(outputFileBusiness)
    writer.writerow(buffer)
    buffer = []

    for line in f:
        jsonLine = json.loads(line.strip())

        hasNullValue = False
        for i in jsonLine:
            if jsonLine[i] == None:
                hasNullValue = True
                break

        if hasNullValue:
            continue

        if jsonLine["city"] == "Philadelphia":
            temp = ""
            for i in jsonLine:
                buffer.append(str(jsonLine[i]).strip())
                if i == "business_id":
                    businessIDs.append(str(jsonLine[i]).strip())
            writer.writerow(buffer)
            buffer = []
outputFileBusiness.close()
print("Done")

#Step 2, Using the business IDs, we find the matching reviews (ignoring those with NULL values). We write them in another CSV
#!WARNING! This takes a LOOOONG time. It produces the filtered reviews file. Be warned.
outputFileReviews = open("filtered_reviews.csv", "w", newline='')

with open("yelp_academic_dataset_review.json", errors="ignore") as f:
    buffer = ["review_id", "user_id", "business_id", "stars",
              "useful", "funny", "cool", "text", "date"]
    writer = csv.writer(outputFileReviews)
    writer.writerow(buffer)
    buffer = []
    counter = 0
    for line in f:
        counter += 1
        try:
            jsonLine = json.loads(line.strip())
        except:
            print(str(counter) + "\n" + line) #Should be removed. Some lines are not good, so we ignore them.
            continue

        hasNullValue = False
        for i in jsonLine:
            if jsonLine[i] == None:
                hasNullValue = True
                break

        if hasNullValue:
            continue

        if jsonLine["business_id"] in businessIDs:
            temp = ""
            for i in jsonLine:
                buffer.append(str(jsonLine[i]).strip().replace("\n", " "))
            writer.writerow(buffer)
            buffer = []
outputFileReviews.close()
print("Done.")

Part A: Distribution¶

For Part A, we try to figure the general distribution of our review_count field within businessData.

Review Count - Bins¶

The first 2 histograms reveal that, as to be expected, very few businesses have more than 2000 reviews. In fact, most have a around 500~! The first histogram shows us this in little detail, due to the vast difference in our scaling. The log plot however, the difference is much clearer due to the logarithmic scale.

Probability Density Function¶

The function is the result of plotting the line roughly above the second histogram. This is to be expected, as the PDF must have the highest density around the start of the plot, and fall off at the end.

Zipf Function¶

The Zipf graph simply provides us with the image of frequency amongst our data. Now much else can be said about it, besides following the Zipf's law.

Part B: Ratings over Time¶

On this part, we test the star rating growth over the duration of time, across all businesses. The proccesses is as follows:

  • For each business, we find the first review's date and store it
  • We then merge the first date with each review according to its business
  • For each review, we find the difference between it and the first review.
  • We divide the difference by 30 to find its index
  • We Group the reviews by index and find the mean star rating

Having done, that we plot the data. At the first graph we see a faint slope downwards which dissapears at the second one. This can tell us that businesses tend to start off with a larger star rating, but overtime return to the general mean, which is around 3.75. Overtime, the mean stays the same. But around 200 months, most businesses have died down. This gives the few businesses that remain the drive over our mean, thus making the data way more chaotic.

The Second graph reinforces our first point. Businesses start off with more stars the first ~20 months, and gradually fall off to the general mean after that time limit.

#This takes roughly a minute to process
def findMonthIndex(firstDate, reviewDate):
    return (abs((firstDate - reviewDate).days)//30)


_business = businessData.merge(reviewsData.groupby(["business_id"])["date"].min(), how="left",
                                       left_on="business_id", right_on="business_id").dropna()

_business = _business.rename({"date":"firstReviewDate"},axis="columns")


indexedMonths = _business[["business_id", "firstReviewDate"]].merge(reviewsData[["business_id","date","stars"]], how="left",
                           left_on="business_id", right_on="business_id")

indexedMonths["monthIndex"] = indexedMonths.apply(lambda x : findMonthIndex(x.firstReviewDate, x.date), axis=1)
_data = indexedMonths.groupby(["monthIndex"])["stars"].mean().reset_index()

Part C: Corellation: Region Price - Stars - Count¶

By reading the RedfinPhila file, we get the regions' median sale price (aka Region price). Afterwards, we similarly calculate the mean stars of each region, as well as the number of businesses. Finally, we plot each value with eachother and calculate the Coefficient and P-Value using Pearsonr Test.

Results¶

For the first graph, with all the data, we see relativly low coefficient and even lower PValues. With the idea to somewhat force a hypothesis from the data, we assume the highest Coefficience (~0.66) to be acceptable. With this in mind, we see high coefficience on the relations SalePrice-Business and SalePrice-Stars. The low PValues confirm the test, and by examining the graphs we can assume:

  • The relatioship between the number of businesses and the regions' price is that the higher the price, the fewer businesses there are.
  • The relationship between the mean stars and the regions' price is the more expensive the region, the higher the star rating.

Results - Over 200k¶

This graph shows similar results with lower coefficiencts. Some P-Values have skyrocketed, while others have remained the same. We will however focus on the previous notes.

  • SalePrice and Business Count has remained somewhat the same. The smaller dataset explains the increase in P-Value, as well as the decrease in Coefficience. We can still hold true the assumption on their relationship.
  • SalePrice and Star Rating has drastically changed! This could be predicted by seeing the graph, but since we ignore the lower priced regions, the star rating on the expensive end remains similar. Therefore there is no significant corelation on the expensive regions and their star rating.

#Part C
realEstateData = pd.read_csv("RedfinPhila.tsv", encoding="latin", sep='\t')
realEstateData["region"] = realEstateData["region"].apply(lambda x: int(x.split(" ")[2]))

#Mean Stars per business
meanStars = businessData.groupby(["postal code"])["stars"].mean().to_frame().sort_values(by="postal code")

#Mean Price by postal code (aka Region)
meanPrice = realEstateData.groupby(["region"])["median_sale_price"].mean().to_frame().sort_values(by="region")
#Business Count by postal code
businessCount = businessData.groupby(["postal code"])["business_id"].count().to_frame()

#Reset indexing for merge
meanPrice = meanPrice.reset_index()
businessCount = businessCount.reset_index()
meanStars = meanStars.reset_index()

#Merge all data to one DataFrame without the region/ZIP codes
estateData = meanPrice.merge(businessCount, how="left", left_on="region", right_on="postal code")\
                    .dropna().drop(["postal code"], axis=1)
estateData = estateData.merge(meanStars, how="left", left_on="region", right_on="postal code")\
                    .dropna().drop(["postal code"], axis=1).drop(["region"], axis=1)
estateData = estateData.rename({"business_id":"Business Count"},axis="columns")

#Plot the data
graph = sns.pairplot(estateData)

#Type on each Graph the Coefficient and P-Value from the pearsonr Test.
dataTypes = ["stars", "Business Count", "median_sale_price"]
for i in range(len(dataTypes)):
    for j in range(len(dataTypes)):
        co, pval = stats.pearsonr(estateData[dataTypes[i]], estateData[dataTypes[j]])
        line = "CoEfficient="+str("{:.4f}".format(co))+ ",\n P-Value=" +str("{:.8f}".format(pval))
        graph.fig.text(1-(0.3*i)-0.25, 0.3*j+0.33, line)
graph.fig.suptitle("All Data", size=16, y=1)

estateData = estateData.loc[estateData["median_sale_price"] > 200_000]
graph = sns.pairplot(estateData)

for i in range(len(dataTypes)):
    for j in range(len(dataTypes)):

Part D: Correlation: Star Rating - Price¶

On this test, we assume a correlation between the star rating and the restaurant's price, using the RestaurantsPriceRange2 attribute to split the data into Expensive and Cheap. The graph generated using this data shows us the mean value, as well as the standard deviation. We can see that there is a difference between the two means, with the expensive restaurants having higher mean stars. The difference in stars is roughly 0.3, which isn't a lot, but it does prove our point. The T-Test's PValue is low enough to confirm our assumption.

Correlation: Star Rating - Attire¶

This time, we assume correlation between star rating and the restaurant's attire. With the attire being either Formal or Casual, we once again plot the data. This time, there is an overlap between the two datasets. Their mean has a small difference, but their deviation crosses each other. Therefore, we can say that usually formal attired restaurants have higher star rating than those with formal, but they have a fair overlap. The T-Test confirms the uncertainty of this hypothesis with a relatively high P-Value.

Part E: Correlation: Good for Dates - Fancy¶

In this test we see if there's a linear correlation between restaurants that are fancy and restaurants that are good for dating. Uing the attributes "Romantic" and "Intimate" for GoodForDate and "Classy" and "Upscale" for Fancy, we calculate the Contigency Table.

Most restaurants fall to neither category, having the highest cluster in the False-False category. This is followed by the False-True category, which we can use to assume that most restaurants that are Fancy, tend to be bad for dating. Suprisingly, the rarest type is the True-False, which is the opposite of the above hypothesis, making very few non-fancy restaurants also good for dating. On the other hand, restaurants that are both good for dating and fancy, seem to have a slightly higher count.

The Chi Value confirms a linear correlation between our data, and the low P-Value confirms it.

#Part E

#Applies the 4 basic values we expect to see as False, should they not exist.
def applyExpectedValues(data):
    if "romantic" not in data:
        data["romantic"] = False
    if "intimate" not in data:
        data["intimate"] = False
    if "classy" not in data:
        data["classy"] = False
    if "upscale" not in data:
        data["upscale"] = False
    return data


#Once more, we pick out the restaurants
restaurants = businessData.loc[businessData["categories"].apply(lambda x: "Restaurants" in x or " Restaurants" in x)]
restaurants = restaurants.copy()
restaurants["attributes"] = restaurants["attributes"].apply(lambda x : eval(x))
#Filter None or non-existing Ambiences
restaurants = restaurants.loc[restaurants["attributes"].apply(lambda x: "Ambience" in x)]
restaurants = restaurants.loc[restaurants["attributes"].apply(lambda x: x["Ambience"] != "None")]

#Create a column only for Ambience for better reading/filtering
restaurants["ambience"] = restaurants["attributes"].apply(lambda x : eval(x["Ambience"]))
#Add non existant values to the dictionary
restaurants["ambience"] = restaurants["ambience"].apply(lambda x: applyExpectedValues(x))

Part Z: Correlation: Type of Business - Regions' Price¶

This test was a bit more tricky. With no easy way to showcase the data, we tried several manners. The main graph we will focus on is the first one we plotted. The manner we decided to compare each region is using the Cosine Difference of their Categorical Vector.

  • The Categorical Vector is a vector of 0s and 1s for each category. All vectors are of the same length.
  • All vectors, after being calculated, have their values divided by the amount of businesses in that region, the calculate their frequency across the region.

Having found this, we compare every region with each other, and find their most similar vector using cosine vector distance. The final plot shows each region, represented by a dot, plotted on their regions' price and their most similar region's vector. While imperfect, this shows that all regions are somewhat similar to each other, regardless regions' price.

Further testing, using heatmaps and 3D plots shows again a great resemblance around the same region across all price ranges. Using Pearsonr Correlation, we get a small value, showing the small correlation in our data. This however is also supported by a large P-Value, showing an uncertainty in our test.

In [9]:
#Part Z
#By finding the best match (and plotting our heatmap later on) we see all businesses gathered around the same area.
#That means that in general, the areas' price does not affect the category.
def findBestMatch(pc):
    global categoricalData
    vector = categoricalData.loc[pc].to_list()
    bestMatch = -1
    bestIndex = -1
    
    for p in categoricalData.index:
        if p == pc:
            continue
        dis = 1-distance.cosine(vector, categoricalData.loc[p].to_list())
        if dis > bestMatch:
            bestMatch = dis
            bestIndex = p
    return bestIndex
        
#Load the mean price of each area
realEstateData = pd.read_csv("RedfinPhila.tsv", encoding="latin", sep='\t')
realEstateData["region"] = realEstateData["region"].apply(lambda x: int(x.split(" ")[2]))
meanPrice = realEstateData.groupby(["region"])["median_sale_price"].mean().to_frame().reset_index()

categoryBusiness = businessData.copy()
categoryBusiness["categories"] = categoryBusiness["categories"].apply(lambda x : [i.strip() for i in x])

#Turn categories into their respective column. ~900 columns for each postal code.
categoricalData = pd.DataFrame()
categoricalData["categories"] = categoryBusiness.groupby(["postal code"]).apply(lambda x : 
                                                  x["categories"].explode().value_counts().to_dict())
categoricalData = categoricalData["categories"].apply(pd.Series).fillna(0).drop(["Restaurants"], axis=1)
#Turn them into a frequency by dividing with the sum of the areas businesses.
categoricalData = categoricalData.apply(lambda x : x / categoricalData.sum(axis=1))

#Find for each region X, a region Y that mostly resembles its vector of categories
bestMatches = categoricalData.reset_index()["postal code"].apply(lambda x : findBestMatch(x))
plotData = categoricalData.reset_index()
plotData["bestMatch"] = bestMatches
plotData = plotData.merge(meanPrice, how="left", left_on="postal code", right_on="region").dropna()

#Plot the mean price of the region with their best match.
deletethis = plt.scatter(plotData["median_sale_price"], plotData["bestMatch"])

co, pval = stats.pearsonr(plotData["bestMatch"], plotData["median_sale_price"])

Part H (Bonus): Correlation Work Hours - Regions' Price¶

Let's form this hypothesis. We have already seen in Part C that there is a correlation in regions' price and the count of businesses. This can be the result of higher rent price in more expensive regions. Let's assume that's true. With this in mind, a business has to put more work hours to stay afloat. With this in mind, using the hours column on each business, we calculate the mean work hours on each region, and compare it to the regions' price.

After plotting the data, we see little difference in the work hours across all regions. In fact, after running the correlation test, we find negative correlation, if any. The P-Value is rather high to say anything for certain, which makes sense, since our dataset for expensive regions is rather small.

Conclusion¶

We can assume our hypothesis wrong. All regions have similar mean work hours, regardless of price. Even if we accept our P-Value of ~0.2 to be enough, the Pearsonr Correlation is too low to be of scientific interest.

#Part H (Bonus)
def countWorkHours(schedule):
    workSchedule = eval(schedule)
    totalHours = 0
    for day in workSchedule.keys():
        w = workSchedule[day].split("-")
        start = datetime.datetime.strptime("1-10-20 " + w[0].split(":")[0] + ":" + w[0].split(":")[1], "%d-%m-%y %H:%M")
        end = datetime.datetime.strptime("1-10-20 " + w[1].split(":")[0] + ":" + w[1].split(":")[1], "%d-%m-%y %H:%M")
        totalHours += (end-start).seconds/3600
    return totalHours  

#Let's go with this hypothesis. Due to the high rent in more expensive areas, the business owners must be working

areaWorkHours = df.groupby("postal code")["workHours"].mean().to_frame().reset_index()
